hands_on_practices.problem:
In the study of the representation theory of finite groups, the degrees of the complex irreducible representations are a fundamental invariant. Consider a finite group $G$ of order $|G|=12$. It is known from character theory that this group has exactly 4 distinct conjugacy classes. The degrees of the irreducible representations, denoted by $\{n_1, n_2, n_3, n_4\}$, are positive integers.

Which of the following sets of integers represents the only possible degrees for the four irreducible representations of such a group $G$?

A. {1, 1, 2, 2}

B. {2, 2, 2, 2}

C. {1, 1, 1, 3}

D. {1, 1, $\sqrt{2}$, $\sqrt{8}$}

E. {1, 2, 3, 6}
